panion to: The Physics of Waiting</span></span>
</div>

<header class=3D"hero fade" style=3D"animation-delay: 0s;">
  <span class=3D"kicker">A field guide for the business</span>
  <h1>Tell them<br>how <em>long</em>.</h1>
  <p class=3D"sub">Why announcing estimated wait time or position in queue =
is one of the highest-return, lowest-cost levers in the contact centre, and=
 how to do it without it backfiring.</p>
</header>
<hr class=3D"rule thick">

<!-- 00: ANTITHESIS -->
<section class=3D"fade" id=3D"antithesis" style=3D"animation-delay: 0.05s;"=
>
  <div class=3D"sec-head">
    <span class=3D"sec-num" style=3D"border-color:var(--ocx-mauve);color:va=
r(--ocx-mauve);">00</span>
    <div class=3D"sec-title-block">
      <span class=3D"sec-word">The honest reckoning</span>
      <h2>The strongest case against everything that follows.</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class=3D"lead">Before building the case for EWT and position announcem=
ents, it is worth making the opposing argument at full strength. A recommen=
dation that cannot survive its own counterargument is not a recommendation =
worth following.</p>

  <div class=3D"antithesis">
    <span class=3D"kicker">Antithesis</span>
    <h2>Seven reasons EWT and PIQ fail or mislead.</h2>

    <div class=3D"at-item">
      <div class=3D"at-num">1</div>
      <div class=3D"at-body"><b>Announcements treat the symptom, not the di=
sease.</b> A queue that is deep enough to require an EWT announcement is, b=
y definition, a queue that is failing. The root cause is structural: too fe=
w agents, poor forecasting, skill fragmentation, or contact drivers that sh=
ould never reach a human agent. Polishing the waiting experience diverts ma=
nagement attention from fixing the queue.</div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"at-item">
      <div class=3D"at-num">2</div>
      <div class=3D"at-body"><b>EWT models break in the conditions where th=
ey matter most.</b> Mass logout events (team meetings, fire drills, shift c=
hangeovers), sudden skill reassignments, system outages, and demand spikes =
all cause EWT to diverge from reality precisely when queues are deepest. Th=
e model is calibrated on steady-state data and fails in the non-steady-stat=
e conditions that produce long queues. At the moment a caller most needs ac=
curate information, the model is most likely to give them bad information.<=
/div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"at-item">
      <div class=3D"at-num">3</div>
      <div class=3D"at-body"><b>Trust erosion is asymmetric and hard to rec=
over from.</b> A correctly delivered EWT builds modest goodwill. An inaccur=
ately delivered EWT degrades trust significantly. The asymmetry is large. Y=
ou cannot easily measure how much institutional trust your EWT system has l=
ost, which means you may be operating with damaged credibility for months w=
ithout knowing it.</div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"at-item">
      <div class=3D"at-num">4</div>
      <div class=3D"at-body"><b>Callback has its own failure modes.</b> Vir=
tual queuing systems are complex. Wrong phone numbers, missed callbacks, ca=
llbacks to voicemail that never get returned, technical failures, and agent=
s calling out of skill all generate secondary contacts and customer effort.=
 A promised callback that does not arrive is worse than no callback offer a=
t all. The operational discipline required to run callbacks well is often u=
nderestimated.</div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"at-item">
      <div class=3D"at-num">5</div>
      <div class=3D"at-body"><b>Self-selection removes callers who might ha=
ve been fine.</b> The balking effect is not purely beneficial. Some callers=
 who balk based on the announcement would have waited without complaint and=
 been satisfied with the interaction. EWT is a blunt instrument: it cannot =
distinguish between the caller who truly cannot wait and the one who just n=
eeded a moment of reassurance. You may be turning away resolvable contacts.=
</div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"at-item">
      <div class=3D"at-num">6</div>
      <div class=3D"at-body"><b>CALD communities and accessibility edge cas=
es are poorly served.</b> EWT announcements are designed for callers with f=
luent comprehension of the announced language, numeracy to convert time int=
o a decision, and a phone environment where they can hear and respond to an=
 IVR prompt. Callers from culturally and linguistically diverse backgrounds=
, elderly callers, callers with cognitive or hearing impairments, and calle=
rs in noisy environments may not benefit at all, and may be disadvantaged b=
y a system designed around a different average user.</div>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"at-item">
      <div class=3D"at-num">7</div>
      <div class=3D"at-body"><b>Sustained deep queues defeat all of it.</b>=
 Everything in this document assumes the queue is cyclically stressed: it w=
ill recover. In a sustained deep queue (weeks of above-capacity demand, chr=
onic understaffing), callback generates a callback backlog, EWT becomes per=
manently inaccurate, position numbers are permanently in crisis range, and =
customers stop trusting announcements entirely. The correct response to a s=
ustained deep queue is not a better announcement strategy. It is emergency =
staffing, automation, and demand reduction. These are not substitutes for e=
ach other.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>With that case on the table: the evidence for well-implemented, accura=
tely modelled EWT and PIQ announcements still favours implementation over s=
ilence, in normal operating conditions, with appropriate calibration and mo=
nitoring. The antithesis above is not a reason to do nothing. It is a list =
of the ways doing this poorly is worse than not doing it at all.</p>
</section>
<hr class=3D"rule">

<!-- 01: WHY -->
<section class=3D"fade" id=3D"why" style=3D"animation-delay: 0.1s;">
  <div class=3D"sec-head">
    <span class=3D"sec-num">01</span>
    <div class=3D"sec-title-block">
      <span class=3D"sec-word">The core problem</span>
      <h2>Uncertainty is a hidden tax on your queue.</h2>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p class=3D"lead">Customers do not just wait. They suffer through not kno=
wing. Research in behavioural queueing consistently finds that the same obj=
ective wait feels longer and triggers abandonment sooner when no informatio=
n is provided. The pain is not just the time. It is the open question of wh=
ether this is ever going to end.</p>
  <p>Customer patience is not a fixed number. It is information-sensitive. =
When callers have no idea how long they will wait, they conservatively aban=
don early. Tell them four minutes and the callers with five-minute patience=
 stay. Tell them nothing and a meaningful fraction of those same callers le=
ave at minute two, because they cannot know whether they are close. <strong=
>Removing that uncertainty is the mechanism. Everything else follows from i=
t.</strong></p>
  <div class=3D"callout warn">
    <div class=3D"ct">Silence inflates abandonment beyond what the queue al=
one predicts.</div>
    <p>Studies of emergency department and call centre queues consistently =
find that removing wait information increases abandonment by 15 to 30% comp=
ared to equivalent queues with basic EWT, even when objective wait is ident=
ical (Hui and Tse, 1996; Whitt, 1999). The queue did not get worse. The unc=
ertainty did.</p>
  </div>
  <div class=3D"callout good">
    <div class=3D"ct">Information restructures the abandonment curve, not j=
ust its level.</div>
    <p>With EWT, callers self-select. Those whose patience genuinely exceed=
s the stated wait stay; those who cannot wait that long leave at the door r=
ather than partway through. This shifts abandonment to the balking stage, b=
efore they have entered the queue, which has very different implications fo=
r average wait and service level for those who remain (Armony, Shimkin and =
Whitt, 2009).</p>
  </div>
</section>
<hr class=3D"rule">

<!-- 02: TWO TYPES -->
<section class=3D"fade" id=3D"types" style=3D"animation-delay: 0.15s;">
  <div class=3D"sec-head">
    <span class=3D"sec-num">02</span>
    <div class=3D"sec-title-block">
      <span class=3D"sec-word">The two options</span>
      <h2>EWT and position: same goal, different mechanisms.</h2>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>There are two standard ways to tell a customer where they stand. They =
have meaningfully different properties for both the customer and your platf=
orm's implementation complexity.</p>
  <div class=3D"twocol-eq">
    <div class=3D"panel">
      <div class=3D"biz" style=3D"font-family:var(--serif);font-size:20px;f=
ont-weight:600;margin-bottom:4px;">Estimated Wait Time</div>
      <div style=3D"font-size:12px;color:var(--clay);font-weight:600;letter=
-spacing:.04em;margin-bottom:12px;">EWT =C2=B7 time-based announcement</div=
>
      <p style=3D"font-size:15px;color:var(--ink-soft);line-height:1.55;mar=
gin:0;">Announces a specific time: "Your estimated wait is approximately fo=
ur minutes." Directly answers the question the customer actually needs answ=
ered. More actionable: they can decide to call back, try another channel, o=
r stay. Requires a live model to compute, and that model can fail in the co=
nditions described in section 00.</p>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"panel">
      <div class=3D"biz" style=3D"font-family:var(--serif);font-size:20px;f=
ont-weight:600;margin-bottom:4px;">Position in Queue</div>
      <div style=3D"font-size:12px;color:var(--clay);font-weight:600;letter=
-spacing:.04em;margin-bottom:12px;">PIQ =C2=B7 ordinal announcement</div>
      <p style=3D"font-size:15px;color:var(--ink-soft);line-height:1.55;mar=
gin:0;">Announces a rank: "You are caller number five in the queue." Easier=
 to compute accurately since it is always a true count. Requires the caller=
 to mentally convert to time. Research shows it is somewhat less effective =
at reducing abandonment than EWT but still meaningfully better than silence=
 (Munichor and Rafaeli, 2007).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class=3D"panel" style=3D"margin-top:18px;">
    <div class=3D"biz" style=3D"font-family:var(--serif);font-size:20px;fon=
t-weight:600;margin-bottom:4px;">Combined (best practice)</div>
    <div style=3D"font-size:12px;color:var(--clay);font-weight:600;letter-s=
pacing:.04em;margin-bottom:12px;">PIQ + EWT, updated periodically</div>
    <p style=3D"font-size:15px;color:var(--ink-soft);line-height:1.55;margi=
n:0;">Provide both: "You are number three in the queue, estimated wait appr=
oximately six minutes." Update EWT every 60 to 90 seconds. This removes bot=
h uncertainties simultaneously: callers know their rank (fairness signal) a=
nd the implied time (decision signal). The combination produces the stronge=
st abandonment reduction in the literature.</p>
  </div>
</section>
<hr class=3D"rule">

<!-- 03: MECHANISM + CALCULATOR -->
<section class=3D"fade" id=3D"mechanism" style=3D"animation-delay: 0.2s;">
  <div class=3D"sec-head">
    <span class=3D"sec-num">03</span>
    <div class=3D"sec-title-block">
      <span class=3D"sec-word">How it actually works</span>
      <h2>Self-selection: the invisible queue manager.</h2>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>The benefit of EWT is not mainly about keeping callers calm. It is abo=
ut triggering a <strong>sorting effect at the front door</strong>. When a c=
aller hears the wait, two things happen: callers whose patience exceeds the=
 announced wait stay in queue; callers whose patience falls below it hang u=
p immediately. Those who balk do so at zero cost to queue capacity and free=
 space for callers who will actually be served.</p>
